{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DyBtzrLpsJg5AXSPB4c4Au","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the problem clearly now:\n\n```\nW0616 08:26:17.478081      13 controller.go:1697] unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80. Deleting.\n```\n\nThe controller is repeatedly saying it cannot find the real backend for `demo-canary-echo-80`. This is why the canary routing is not working.\n\nIn nginx-ingress, for canary routing to work:\n1. There must be a \"primary\" Ingress (canary-stable) that defines the host\n2. There must be a \"canary\" Ingress (canary-canary) with the canary annotation enabled\n3. The canary backend service must have active endpoints\n\nThe error suggests that even though the canary-echo endpoints are visible, the controller's internal store isn't finding them. The \"real backend\" reference in this error is actually about the canary backend itself—the controller can't locate the service that the canary Ingress is trying to route to.\n\nThe controller is looking for `demo-canary-echo-80` but failing to find it, even though we verified that `canary-echo.demo.svc:80` is working. I'm wondering if the issue is how the endpoints are being resolved—the controller uses the service port (80) not the container port (5678), so that should be fine. But the error message is specifically about the canary-echo service as the alternative backend, not about finding the primary backend.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the error \"unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80\" means the controller can't find a primary/stable hostname to pair the canary backend with. There should be a primary Ingress for `canary.example.com` that the canary backend merges into, but the controller isn't finding it. Looking at the error more closely, there's also a message about trying to merge `demo-stable-echo-80` into `canary-alt.example.com`, which doe