{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TTWaLF5YRbPZDvnoqnmtvd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The nginx config for `canary.example.com` only has a `location /` that routes to `stable-echo`, with no canary routing. The canary configuration (`canary-canary` Ingress) is not being picked up.\n\nThe issue is the controller message: `unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80. Deleting.`\n\nThis means the controller can't match the `canary-echo:80` backend (the canary Ingress backend) with a \"real\" backend path in the primary Ingress. But why?\n\nIn nginx-ingress, when a canary Ingress is processed, the controller looks for the primary Ingress for the same host and tries to find the path that matches. \n\nThe primary Ingress `canary-stable` has `/health` and `/` (both pointing to stable-echo), while the canary Ingress `canary-canary` has `/` pointing to canary-echo. The paths should match, so I need to dig into the nginx-ingress source to understand why the matching logic is failing.\n\nLooking at the controller error `unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80. Deleting.` — this comes from the nginx-ingress controller when processing canary Ingresses. The controller tries to find a corresponding backend in the primary Ingress for each canary path, and if it can't find one, it deletes the alternative backend. The issue is that even though both Ingresses have a `/` path, the matching logic isn't finding the primary backend for the canary path.\n\nI'm wondering if the problem is with `pathType: Exact` — maybe switching to `pathType: Prefix` would help. Or perhaps the canary Ingress needs to define all the same paths as the primary Ingress, not just a subset. Since the primary has both `/health` and `/` but the canary only has `/`, the controller might be unable to establish the proper mapping between them.\n\nWait, rereading the error more carefully — \"unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80\" — this could mean the controller can't locate active endpoints for the canary service, even though we verified they exist. There might be a timing issue with how the controller's endpoint store is syncing. Let me try deleting and reapplying the canary Ingress now that everything should be fully ready.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":466,"cache_read_input_tokens":61946,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":466},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e2fd028f-f289-4ccb-a409-2b47e5cd3f27","uuid":"911c8bd5-6192-4bb4-92a9-dc53d6fc76a8","request_id":"req_011Cc6czPwXahPycrmdBjZPb"}
