{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017pwFnf6WNF9ViVxLdi4Phv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the critical issue now! Look at this line in the nginx config:\n\n```nginx\nset $proxy_upstream_name \"upstream-default-backend\";\n```\n\nThis should be `set $proxy_upstream_name \"demo-stable-echo-80\"` but it's set to `upstream-default-backend`! This is why we're getting 404s - the location block for `canary.example.com /` is routing to the DEFAULT backend (which returns 404) instead of `stable-echo`.\n\nThe ingress says:\n- `$service_name \"stable-echo\"` - correct\n- `$service_port \"80\"` - correct\n- `$proxy_upstream_name \"upstream-default-backend\"` - WRONG! This should be `demo-stable-echo-80`\n\nThis is the root cause. The controller has the Ingress info correct but the upstream is being set to the default backend. The `demo-stable-echo-80` backend exists in the list, but its Lua balancer endpoints aren't being registered even though the service has endpoints available.\n\nLooking at the backends list again, `demo-stable-echo-80` is definitely there alongside the other backends, yet the nginx config is still pointing to `upstream-default-backend` instead. This suggests the nginx template isn't correctly mapping the backend name to the upstream variable.\n\nExamining the nginx config more closely...\n\nContinuing with the nginx configuration...\n\nThe `$proxy_upstream_name` variable being set to `upstream-default-backend` in the template is likely just a fallback value. The Lua balancer code runs at request time and overwrites it based on the actual routing logic, using variables like `$namespace`, `$ingress_name`, `$service_name`, `$service_port`, and `$location_path` to determine which backend should handle the request. So if `demo-stable-echo-80` isn't being selected, the issue is probably in how the Lua code is looking up or matching the backend.\n\nBut wait—we're getting a 404 from nginx itself, not a 502 Bad Gateway. A 502 would indicate the upstream had no endpoints or the Lua balancer selected a bad upstream. A 404 means the request didn't match any server or location block at all. The config has a server block for `canary.example.com` with `location /`, so the 404 shouldn't be happening unless the path matching is stricter than expected. I'm wondering if the `pathType: Exact` with path `/` is being translated to nginx's `location = /` (exact match only) rather than `location /` (prefix match). So maybe nginx-ingress treats `pathType: Exact` for the root path the same way as `Prefix`, both resulting in `location /`. The real problem could be that the Lua balancer is hitting a 404 because `demo-stable-echo-80` has no registered backend endpoints. Let me dig into the backend details from the debug output to understand what's actually configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3332,"cache_read_input_tokens":68380,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3332},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e2fd028f-f289-4ccb-a409-2b47e5cd3f27","uuid":"393f6c6b-5c86-45bb-8ec2-46256ce4d970","request_id":"req_011Cc6d9eaMGfgcMBLpTSL69"}
