{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FjZKiBnMtzMexVreHyCHAn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So `demo-stable-echo-80` has an endpoint `10.244.0.173:5678`. The Lua balancer should be able to route to it.\n\nBut wait - is the Lua balancer actually using this to set the upstream? The nginx config has `set $proxy_upstream_name \"upstream-default-backend\"` as the static value, and then the Lua code should dynamically set it to `demo-stable-echo-80`.\n\nBut we're getting 404! A 404 from nginx means the location was NOT found. But there IS a `location /` block for `canary.example.com`. \n\nThe 404 might not be from location matching at all - it could be coming from the Lua balancer when it fails to route to the backend. Let me check what's actually happening with a verbose curl request to see the full response details. I'm also realizing the `demo-stable-echo-80` backend uses `10.244.0.173:5678`, but the nginx-ingress config statically sets `$proxy_upstream_name` to `upstream-default-backend`, so the Lua balancer code needs to override that.\n\nActually, wait - that 404 response with the `<center><h1>404 Not Found</h1></center>` HTML is definitely nginx's default error page, not the backend's plain text response. So nginx itself is returning the 404, which means the location matching is failing somehow. But there's a `location /` block for `canary.example.com`, so this shouldn't happen unless... the `ssl_redirect` setting is interfering. It's set to true, which might be forcing HTTP requests to redirect to HTTPS before they even hit the location blocks.\n\nActually no, that would give a 301/302 redirect, not a 404. Let me reconsider - the curl request is going to port 80 on the ingress-nginx controller service with `Host: canary.example.com`, and the nginx config has both the listen directives and the matching server block. The `location /` should definitely match. Maybe there's a default server block or another location that's matching first instead of the intended one.\n\nLet me check the actual HTTP response headers with verbose curl output to see what's happening, and then examine all the server blocks in the nginx config to see if the controller even has the right configuration loaded.\n\nActually, the issue might be that the nginx config was updated but hasn't been reloaded yet. Looking at the controller logs, the last reload happened at 08:24:38, which was before the canary-canary Ingress was created. Since then, the canary backend was deleted and then re-applied, but no reload occurred because of the error. So the current nginx config I'm looking at is from that earlier reload when only canary-stable was applied. The Lua balancer should have demo-stable-echo-80 configured, but we're still getting 404 for the stable request even though the nginx config shows location / routing to stable-echo.\n\nWait, I just noticed the ssl_redirect setting in the nginx config. If ssl_redirect is set to true and the request comes in on HTTP port 80, nginx would redirect to HTTPS. But if HTTPS isn't properly configured for this host, that redirect could be causing issues. Let me check the exact response with verbose curl output to see what's happening. The Lua rewrite script would redirect HTTP requests to HTTPS for the same hostname, but if there's no HTTPS listener or certificate configured, that could cause unexpected behavior. Let me run a verbose curl to see what the actual response headers are.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1826,"cache_read_input_tokens":71712,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1826},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e2fd028f-f289-4ccb-a409-2b47e5cd3f27","uuid":"8e8e56b5-0